Zero-interest club or Negative interest club.
Brussels - In most of the past decade, the central bank has made only limited progress in containing the powerful global deflationary forces.
The Federal Reserve has maintained interest rates at zero since 2008, and has also carried out unprecedented balance sheet expansions through multiple rounds of large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have also followed the Federal Reserve's footsteps, implementing their own versions of what is called "quantitative easing" (QE).
Inflation has seen no reasonable rise anywhere.
Despite these countries' struggles against deflationary pressures, their monetary policies – as well as their economic performances – are diverging.
The US and the UK now have sufficiently strong growth to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are ramping up QE, pushing policy long-term rates further into negative territory.
The reason behind this divergence.
Shortly, it is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had chronic current account deficits, thus being debtors, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, thus being creditors.
Negative interest rates are beneficial to debtors but detrimental to creditors, so the introduction of negative interest rates globally after the financial crisis has stimulated the recovery of the US and the UK, but has had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
To date, most creditor nations – countries with persistent large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland – have had negative interest rates, not just long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also medium-term bonds.
This is not a good thing.
Despite the limited effect of low interest rates, these central banks continue to pursue this policy.
If you suggest that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will dodge the issue and counter with the concept that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy – which appears to be unassailable at first glance.
But in reality, it is full of loopholes.
A basic principle in economics courses is the phenomenon of "backward-bending savings supply curves": under certain conditions, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce the income of savers, they will cut back on spending, especially if they have a target of saving for retirement.
These are not negations of the general rule - which forms the basis of modern monetary policy - that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other expenditures.
The impact varies due to the differing debt situations of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors will naturally outnumber debtors.
For a country with a large foreign debt, the situation is reversed.
Therefore, the effectiveness of the lower bound monetary policy differs between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not significant, because foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, mainly due to the leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis, the net foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies have become large and increasingly diversified.
In reality, however, leverage continues to rise at the national level.
Despite a general reduction in current account imbalances since the financial crisis, they have not been reversed.
This implies that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor status, diverging from deficit economies.
Some major commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them exceptions to the trend of foreign asset position divergence.
Since the 2014 oil price crash, the wealth trend of these countries has reversed.
Their export earnings plummeted sharply – many countries lost half – forcing them to run deficits, relying on massive sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
The sharp reduction in spending has become unavoidable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem – to some extent – is a luxury problem – ensuring consumers spend the unexpected windfall from declining import prices.
However, in creditor nations, negative interest rates seem to have failed to advance this objective; in fact, some external surpluses have even continued to grow.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although the eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, it also has debtor countries within it.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
However, the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, thereby continuing to increase the debtor-creditor asymmetry.
Most noteworthy is that since the financial crisis erupted, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, implying that the surplus Germany accumulated during this period has exceeded its historical total.
According to the current trend, Germany's creditor position may rise from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank chiefs should be patient.
In fact, economists have supported the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank chiefs are less keen on stimulating short-term economic growth.
But central bank chiefs seem impatient rather than patient, worrying about low inflation, despite the output gap gradually being filled, and the US and Japan having achieved full employment.
Central bank chiefs of debtor nations must stop using monetary easing, which may not be beneficial to production, to manipulate the economy.
Contrary to that, they should allow themselves to recover and develop at their own pace, even if it is slow, and wait for the base effect of the oil price drop to dissipate.
European Central Bank President Draghi has recently acknowledged that the current monetary policy stance may not be effective in today's global environment.
Implementing more of the same policies is not a solution.
